The `waitForFunction` checks `sessionSwitchInProgress` and `chatBatchLoading` but omits `state.subscribed`. The `waitForChatSessionReady` helper in `websocket.spec.js` (line 51–62) gates on all three: `state.subscribed && !(state.sessionSwitchInProgress || state.chatBatchLoading)`. Without confirming the subscription is live, injecting a `system-event` immediately after this guard clears could still arrive before the frontend has registered its WebSocket event handlers, causing the event to be silently dropped and making the tests intermittently flaky once they're un-fixme'd.

```suggestion
		await page.waitForFunction(
			async () => {
				var appScript = document.querySelector('script[type="module"][src*="js/app.js"]');
				if (!appScript) return false;
				var appUrl = new URL(appScript.src, window.location.origin);
				var prefix = appUrl.href.slice(0, appUrl.href.length - "js/app.js".length);
				var state = await import(`${prefix}js/state.js`);
				return state.subscribed && !(state.sessionSwitchInProgress || state.chatBatchLoading);
			},
			{ timeout: 10_000 },
		);
